  "prompt": "How is it possible to open an account in TD Ameritrade for non-US residents?",
  "response": "It's possible for non-US residents to open a TD Ameritrade account, **but it's no longer possible to open new accounts as a retail investor.**\n\n**TD Ameritrade was acquired by Charles Schwab and new retail accounts are no longer being opened under the TD Ameritrade name.**\n\n**Here's the history and what you need to know:**\n\n*   **TD Ameritrade's Position (Now Historical):** Historically, TD Ameritrade *did* allow non-US residents to open accounts. However, the process was more complex and required specific documentation.\n\n*   **Charles Schwab Acquisition:** In 2020, Charles Schwab acquired TD Ameritrade.  Schwab is in the process of migrating all TD Ameritrade accounts over to Schwab.\n\n*   **Current Status - No New TD Ameritrade Accounts:** Because of the merger, **TD Ameritrade is no longer opening new retail brokerage accounts.** You can't open a new account directly with them as a new customer.\n\n*   **Schwab International Account:** If you are a non-US resident looking to invest in the US market, you'll need to look into opening a Schwab International Account.\n\n**Steps to Explore (Through Charles Schwab):**\n\n1.  **Visit Charles Schwab International:**  Go directly to the Charles Schwab International website to get accurate and up-to-date information.  This is the key starting point.\n2.  **Review Eligibility:** Carefully examine the eligibility requirements for international accounts.  Requirements can vary based on your country of residence.\n3.  **Gather Required Documents:** Prepare the necessary documentation. This usually includes:\n    *   **Proof of Identity:** Passport or other government-issued photo ID.\n    *   **Proof of Address:** Utility bill, bank statement, or other official document showing your current address.\n    *   **Tax Identification Number (TIN):**  This is the equivalent of a Social Security Number (SSN) in your country.  This is critical for tax reporting purposes.\n    *   **Additional Documentation:** Schwab may require other documents depending on your country of residence and the type of account you're opening.\n\n4.  **Complete the Application:** Fill out the online application form carefully and accurately.\n5.  **Fund Your Account:** Once your account is approved, you'll need to fund it.  Schwab will likely offer various funding options, such as wire transfers.\n\n**Important Considerations for Non-US Residents:**\n\n*   **Tax Implications:**  US taxes are complex for non-residents.  You will likely be subject to a 30% withholding tax on dividends and interest (though this may be reduced by tax treaties between the US and your country). Capital gains taxes also apply.  It is **essential** to consult with a qualified tax advisor in your country and, ideally, one familiar with US tax regulations for non-residents.\n*   **Country-Specific Restrictions:**  Your country may have restrictions on investing in foreign securities.  Check with your local financial authorities to ensure compliance.\n*   **Currency Exchange:**  Be aware of currency exchange rates and fees when converting your local currency to US dollars and vice versa.\n*   **Language Support:** Confirm that Schwab provides adequate language support in your preferred language, especially for important documents and customer service.\n*   **Account Minimums:** Check if Schwab has minimum deposit requirements for international accounts.\n*   **Customer Service:** Ensure that Schwab offers reliable customer service that is accessible from your location and in your language.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nWhile TD Ameritrade *used* to offer accounts to non-US residents, this is no longer the case.  Your best bet is to explore Charles Schwab International accounts and understand the requirements, tax implications, and restrictions involved. Consulting with a financial advisor and a tax professional is highly recommended before making any investment decisions.\n",
